The army bought for 445 km of ropes used for explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defence had purchased 224 km.
The army therefore has reserves for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the ropes is two to four years maximum.
The military bought detonator cords from the STV Group for 40 million kroner.
The General Staff gave as a reason for the achat of an enormous amount of detonating cords to MF DNES that the soldiers use 60 km per year.
According to the reserve calculations to be held by the pyrotechnicians of the army, which MF DNES has contacted, it appears that even the generals, officers with a command, secretaries or cleaning staff should have an explosives exercise every year.
Alexander Vondra, Minister of Defence and Vlastimil Picek, commander of the army are no exception.
Only to argue the army's annual consumption of 60 km of detonating ropes.
This distance corresponds to 25,000 explosions.
And even if that were true, the army's reserves could be kept there for 10 years.
If, on the contrary, it would be true that for the basic training of each of the new professionals it is enough to have more than 2 m of detonating ropes, as the experts say, it means that the army with its new purchase has ensured - with also the consumption of special units and engineering - reserves for the 225 years mentioned.
However, the soldiers of the Rapid Response Brigade recently complained to Minister Vondra that they have almost no ammunition for their handguns and that shooting sessions are limited due to the need for money.
There is no mention of the lack of laundry.
"And I don't mind if they buy so many detonating cords from us."
“And that’s their decision and they really know what they’re doing.”
"For us the army is a good customer that we strive as traders to satisfy," says STV Group sales director Jan Decky.
Jan Pejsek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defense, argues that hundreds of kilometers of detonating cords will be used by the army for 10 years.
Jan Decky of STV Group, however, reports of only four years of life of the detonating cords and the pyrotechnicians of the police and army of only two years.
"If they are perfectly stored in the depots, it can be up to four years," says one who does not want his name published in view of criticism of the army.
As the life span has passed, each ammunition must be tested to see if it remains intact and does not threaten the life of the soldier.
These tests, however, are not free and still cost money.
The department's other argument is a rebate for the quantity of 445 km of detonating ropes.
"They cost us 60 percent less than last year's supply of 245 km," said spokesman Pejsek, who interprets the opinion of the defense ministry's buyers.
Only to compare: the annual consumption of detonating cords of police pyrotechnics that neutralize ammunition from the Second World War or those after the Soviet army, does not exceed 1500 meters.
And the police always order only the necessary amount of ammunition to be used before the end of their lifespan.
This was established for the safety of pyrotechnicians and to be able to obtain more flexible types of detonating ropes more modern and more reliable.
The Ministry of Defense today has big problems for the neutralization of tens of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand men was preparing to move, heading for the Rhine.
What awaits in a few years this Czech army that MF DNES has contacted: neutralize hundreds of kilometers of old detonating cords that it buys today "cheap".
To this day, I benefit from contacts that I have obtained through the contests.
The franchise sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun win the Best Individual Entrepreneur competition.
The winner of last year’s Best Individual Entrepreneur competition was 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukas Pytloun.
His adventure to success is like in a movie.
Lukas Pytloun loved to travel.
And abroad, he realized that in Liberec there was a lack of a quality hosting site at a reasonable price.
From his savings on what he had earned while working abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small building of 5 apartments half demolished.
Knowing that he was still a student in the third year of higher education, it was a courageous action.
“The relationship between quality and price of accommodation in our region made me want to do something,” says Lucas Pytloun.
He began renting the first rebuilt apartment to foreign workers.
He reinvested the profit in the building which he converted into a pension with 54 beds.
Since then, his entrepreneurial activity has allowed him to open in Liberec 4 pensions, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of almost 300 beds of all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of them was until recently the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year there was another one of the same quality.
"We have just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrova U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other candidates for the Pytloun hotel franchise showed up," the number one entrepreneur of last year.
"And for the sale of the license for the operation of a large-scale hotel the victory in the Entrepreneur of the Year contest has served well," adds Pytloun with appreciation.
The victory brought him more popularity and being known in Liberec and its surroundings.
"People recognized me on the streets, congratulated me often and, I have to say, it was very pleasant," he recalls.
He recommends participation in this competition to all those who are striving to do something.
It is not necessary to win but any opportunity to be visible is good.
He says he uses his contacts and knowledge to this day that he could not have obtained in any other way.
"With those I met through the contest, I began to maintain business relationships regularly.
According to him, the fame related to the success also had an impact on the employees.
And he's about 70.
“I observe in them above all the loyalty and pride of having engaged in something that has generally been recognized.”
“This is not, by far, the only result of my personal work, but the result of good work by all of us together.
“Only my name is pushed forward,” says Lucas Pytloun modestly.
I wish my successor a better year than the one we had at Farmet.
The euphoria of victory was quickly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the sense of purpose of the winner Farmet has the worst moments behind him.
The one who came to get the prize in Slovansky dum for the first place of the contest for the Firm of the Year organized by Vodaphone last year is Karel Zdarsky the owner of the company Farmet.
The jury rewarded the efforts with which it transformed a tooling workshop in Ceska Skalice into a company with a turnover of 100 million kroner.
"I can say that the award has not only encouraged me, my employees and increased our self-confidence in fighting the competition," said the winner of last year's competition.
At the beginning of Farmet's history there was a desire to do something useful.
And so when the state proposed to Karel Zdrasky's father to rent the small workshop as compensation after the confiscation of property by the communists, he did not hesitate long, refused a career in a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with a few comrades in his father's entourage for the manufacture of plastic bathtubs.
Not long after they began to specialize in presses for vegetable oil.
After eighteen years, it became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company was known even in the non-specialized public after the success obtained in the contest through the media.
“Not only have our customers started to really get to know the Farmet brand but also the foreign partners who have started to realize that they are collaborating with a company that has achieved the greatest success in its home country,” says Karel Zdarsky.
But the past year has not been spent in Farmet only in the euphoria of victory.
The company's valuation was based on 2008 and part of 2009 economic results.
And precisely in 2009 it was the most difficult year for the sale of engineering machinery.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect citizens, companies were forced to stop their investment projects and start limiting their purchases of new materials and technologies.
"Obviously we have not escaped this situation."
“Revenue fell by 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even lay off,” Zdarsky said.
A viable society must know that from time to time unpopular measures must be taken.
But they managed the situation correctly and retained beneficial results even if they were inferior to those they had before the crisis.
At Farmet, however, they continued uncompromisingly to invest in research and development.
"We built with the endowments a training and research center, strengthened the company's presentation in international trade fairs and won the main awards in national exhibitions," says Zdarsky.
Everything suggests that the crisis is behind them.
The number of employees is rising and so is the number of employees.
"To the new winner I wish this pleasant feeling of victory but in a calm atmosphere," said Karel Zdarsky.
The investigation that eliminates foolish regulations.
The Absurdity of the Year survey is for the fourth time a part of the business clan.
Some absurd regulations have been removed.
The unglorious winner of this year's Absurdity Survey of the Year was the requirement to bring into offices documents that officials can obtain online.
More than a third of the 4,000 voters voted for it.
For example, the social affairs administration requested a paper extract from the commercial register, while the grievor could obtain it in two mouse clicks.
It changes thanks to the investigation.
“The Czech Social Insurance Administration will no longer ask for the trade register extract for insurance payment checks,” said Jana Buranova, a spokeswoman for the Czech Social Insurance Administration (CSSZ).
Bringing out all the regulations and decrees that companies and entrepreneurs must comply with in the Czech Republic and removing those that are absurd is the meaning of this Absurdity of the Year contest.
This survey is again this year for the fourth time a part of the business clan organized by Hospodarske noviny and has even greater popularity.
If last year 3000 voters showed up, it is at least 4000 this year that brought their vote.
And it is not surprising, there are in our country the most diverse legal obligations that only slow down the company, and,this, more and more.
"We may be among the number of documents to be filled out for tax returns at the top places in the world," says Karel Havlicek of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
The simplification of entrepreneurial activity has become a proclaimed goal of all governments in recent years.
Compared to the whole world, the situation in the Czech Republic is not improving at all.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic ranks 74th in terms of conditions for the company, 8 places more than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was first established in 2006 and continues each year under the same scenario.
Anyone can report the administrative and bureaucratic absurdities from April to the end of September each year, the last deadline before the closing of the competition.
To report there is the website www.firmaroku.cz. Then, the organizer of the contest selects seven candidates for the "anti-price" and lets the public vote during the month of October on the website www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and on www.ihned.cz.
The Absurdity that received the highest number of votes is declared the winner.
Until last year's last investigation, it is a hundred, or more exactly 105 regulations and decrees that have lost their sense of existence.
The comments are sent by the entrepreneurs but also the professional unions and the professors.
Among the "finalists" of the competition, so among the nominees is for example the obligation that vehicles for the maintenance of highways and highways pay the tolls, or that contractors with twenty employees, repainted two offices and two toilets every two years.
The list of seven proposals is published on the competition website.
The proclamation of the competition, which always begins at the beginning of November on Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of a happening in which political and public figures regularly participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodova, Director of the Association for Small and Medium-sized Enterprises of the Czech Republic, and Petr Kuzel, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Czech Republic, attended the highlight of the competition.
"Economic prosperity cannot work when the state puts money in the legs of entrepreneurs and for that my goal is to remove, every year, at least three dozen paragraphs that today only complicate the business," said Martin Kocourek, the Minister of Industry and Trade.
The effort to suppress absurd decrees is not a swordsmanship in the water.
In 2007, what people did not like was the obligation of entrepreneurs to declare three days in advance at the office for the individual business at the place where the business is located, the intention to go to an exhibition or a pilgrimage with a stand.
