At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public competition
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives handcuffed the local entrepreneur and real estate dealer Lubos. G.
The latter had endeavoured to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a request for restitution in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a specific candidate.
He was to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"At the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider trading in the context of a public tender and competition," Plzen Prosecutor Antonie Zelena told the Pravo newspaper, knowing that it is forbidden to provide further explanations as the investigation is ongoing.
The police released the 46-year-old entrepreneur after 24 hours.
To find out how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in the light of so little official information.
Asked by Pravo, Lubomira Cerna, a spokeswoman for the Lands Fund, said that the police had actually made an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
"It was a customer and in no case an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has as its real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land under the Land Act" and is set up when there are several candidates beneficiaries of law.
"These persons propose, as part of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to restitution which must be settled before the value of the land is announced."
"According to the proposed rights, a ranking of the buyers is put in place and the Lands Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights," the spokesperson said.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the appeal and since he himself is also a beneficiary because having purchased a large number of restitution rights, he had proposed to the candidates in the field not to participate in the competition.
And he was probably cashing in by withdrawing.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terrains).
He was included in the case of the former head of the FdT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted for publishing land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been issued.
For example, Lubos G. had obtained land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the access road to the industrial zone of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was forced to accept because otherwise it risked endangering the construction by a blockade of the land.
Households will pay an additional 100 kroner per month for housing.
As of January, households will have to pay a surcharge not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
From January onwards, families will have to draw up to 100 kroner a month more than they do now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be close to 100 kroner per year for apartment households more than currently.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the sensitive development to encourage the production of renewable energy, in particular photovoltaic batteries.
Gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
One can also count an additional hundred crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the larger municipalities that plan the price increase.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 kroner more per month for central heating from January, and families in Liberec will pay more than 1000 kroner per year.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sanitation in case the city increases the infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the Pragians will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the entire country.
In Northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will for example increase significantly in the 450 thousand apartments for rent from January, that is to say at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2,500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase it up to 100 percent.
Those who do not agree with the new increase in rents will be brought before the courts by the company.
The regulated rents people pay in nearly 300 thousand apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very slowly.
The fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for recurrence are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of doctors encountering cases similar to admissions in hospital children's departments.
“Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to get drunk.”
"The trend is really towards strong alcohols," said Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children's department at the hospital in Horovice in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to snatch a daddy bottle out of the closet, it's sometimes whiskey, but fernet and vodka prevail."
"Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and so not smell it," explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokeswoman for Motol Hospital, also gives him reason.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
"It is now alcohol in fashion, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought back from the house," Jurinova added.
According to the Head of Department Pélikan, seeing drunk children aged thirteen to fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced ten years precisely in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wide surroundings completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized four times like this.
"She started her career at twelve when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood with in addition a mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Centre at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was away for 48 hours," said the Director of the Department.
It is precisely the disinterest of the parents or their unusual tolerance to the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that are the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
According to specialists, however, we are not talking about addiction, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the word alcoholic we mean a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that is not found in children."
"In those who use alcohol repeatedly, it is rather a significantly unfavorable socio-family back-ground," explained the Head of Department Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistic.
Drunk children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or police, are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, there are three seasonal waves according to Pelikan that can be counted on: Witches' Day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"Of course I experienced at the witches' day an admission of 7 drunk children at once," Pélikan said.
The drunk child who spent the night in the hospital under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who went home and suffered the next day from "hangover".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and a lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off because they have an excellent evening and then a gentle awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They’re just surprised at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils the good mood of patients at least with the bill to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and hospitalization on an intensive care bed can be up to tens of thousands of crowns.
“Once in a while, I applied this as a way of educating these children by counting how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend all summer on seasonal work to pay for a single evening,” Pelikan added.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their regressive managements, which should recover from the parents the expenses related to care, do not treat cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two of the five L-159 aircraft, for which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of anyone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad in the course of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were in service with the Czech Army and were in flight.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seater versions of the L-159.
These are currently parked at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the Omnipol firm - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the aircraft from Vodochody is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seater aircraft planned for the exchange were taken from long-storage aircraft without causing additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defence."
"The two-seaters L-159 T1 were exchanged in the state," said Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not be without two-seaters since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aero Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 cars into two two-seaters.
The military took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introduce the aircraft in the equipment of some countries of the Alliance.
“In the contract it is clearly stated that the one who takes the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used for the training of pilots from NATO member countries.”
"It is therefore up to the person who is considering how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was endorsed last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not issue a call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
the Defence Directorate argued that the exchange ensures a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and only used 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been chosen in a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index finger than the ring finger is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have the index finger longer than the ring finger are at a lower risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men before age 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a shorter right hand index than the annular one.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index index longer than the annular the risk however fell to 33 percent, for men before 60 years the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he was aware of the study but did not believe the relationship between finger length and cancer was "completely demonstrated".
