Go to hell, warrior!
Is the Splatter movie an artificial film?
Director Nicolas Winding Refn explores the limits of the ancient genre with his film, "Walhalla Rising", the epic of the fighter.
What audience did Danish director Nicolas Winding Refn think of when he shot “Walhalla Rising”?
A Viking warrior (Mads Mikkelsen) possessing only one eye is taken prisoner; he frees himself from his executioner and, with almost supernatural force, eliminates his opponents one after the other. This seems ideal for young male spectators looking for a bloody action, precisely because our hero will wait for those without brutal assassination methods.
On the other hand, until the end of the film, the blind man does not say a word about his real name. Even the other characters let escape, at most, at the turn of one or two sentences some horrible cries of agony.
Otherwise, nothing is said and we feast on the incredibly beautiful mountainous landscape of Scotland that forms the backdrop of the Viking universe, about a thousand years ago.
This would be ideal for mature filmmakers with an interest in existentialism and excellent travellings.
When a film targets several target groups, it is a pity that they exclude each other.
The director Winding Refn is considered, since the release of "Pusher", his trilogy related to the fierce and stylish drug dealer, as a kind of Danish Quentin Tarantinon, but he refuses to bring a little more mood to the mainstream or introduce a little less brutality to the art and trial cinema.
Most fans of art cinema must experience horror in the face of the brain that spreads all around and to the intestines.
Action movie lovers die of boredom, when the blind man embarks, for reasons that can be freely interpreted, with a group of violent Christian missionaries on a ship bound for Jerusalem; they are drowned for an eternity by calm and mist before the crew arrives in America and continues to be silent.
It is not surprising then that "Walhalla Rising" has not found any film distributors in Germany and exists only in the DVD format.
It is mainly because of the magnificent images of misery that deserved some attention, but also because the image of a thrilling film, from time to time, hides behind a pretentious and bloody appearance.
It is not about dialogues in this film, nor about coherent action, everything is atmosphere, a feverish dream transformed into a film.
The spectator cannot escape it.
Refn barely gives him a moment of relaxation and slowly cuts his throat with chilly images and a gloomy soundtrack, but above all with an elusive hatred that springs from the hearts of the characters.
Only a young blond boy, who stands faithfully beside the blind man, preserves a certain innocence, all the others are animated by anger.
Most of all, the blind hero whose motives are never known, but who returns from hell at any time to fight enemies and temporarily allies by transforming himself into a warrior, is perhaps the devil himself.
It represents rot, but perhaps also, only for those who are, anyway, rotten.
"Walhalla Rising" is an enigmatic film that can be hated or admired, whose purpose is annoyance, enthusiasm and wonder.
A traumatic experience.
Mysterious Earthworks
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new information regarding a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this subject, much less to submit to the controls of the agency.
On the night of September 5-6, 2007 around midnight, at least four Israeli F-15 fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the bank of the Euphrates; the largest nearby town is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
Its name appears in the IAEA documents, because it refers to the reactor that Syria has apparently built with the help of North Korea in parallelepiped stone, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electric current.
According to a U.S. intelligence briefing, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the neighboring locality, el-Kibar, would be well suited to produce plutonium, which would allow the manufacture of atomic weapons.
On the other hand, this technique has been valid since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a presentation video featuring blurred satellite images.
Through computer-assisted animation, it indicated the likely location of each reactor component prior to the destruction of the plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even the interior of it.
It appears that the reactor was about to be commissioned, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, little more information is available than at the time, and even, with time, the mystery thickens more and more.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before this attack, the CIA was certain that Syria had built a reactor at el-Kibar, but had little clue that the country was developing "an active nuclear weapons program."
Some intelligence agents in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and speak only of an "alleged reactor", even though they regard the CIA's presentation as "plausible".
They lack tangible evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he ensures he is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior U.N. diplomat gave only a laconic answer in the summer when he said the IAEA had "sufficient documents to ask questions."
The Syrians certainly hastily removed the rubble from the “unused military building” and proceeded to a methodical flattening of the land.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of human-produced uranium in al-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA received satellite images from commercial vendors from one Member State showing the moment directly following the attack, which appear to be more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, possibly Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always assured that it has never carried out a secret atomic program and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus claims that the uranium found on the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after the particle analysis, calling it implausible.
Since that time, Damascus has refused any discussion on this, as well as on satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to carry out a second inspection at the al-Kibar site and denies access to the debris of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel remains obstinately silent.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister in office at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on this."
Thus, the investigation into this case has been going on for a long time since June 2008 without a result being achieved and it "is increasingly turning into a serious credibility problem for the Agency", as a high-ranking Western diplomat serving at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna acknowledges, ultimately it is a serious violation of the nuclear-weapon-ban treaty.
The IAEA considers that in order to make progress, it is necessary to clarify the existence of the other three facilities that must have a "functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
So far, the inspectors have not indicated which facilities are involved, what their function is or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the newspaper "Süddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA respectively as Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also from the names of the neighboring towns.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington has identified these locations and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would most likely be one of the suspicious objects.
It may be located at or directly adjacent to a military base, which is exactly why Syria is denying IAEA inspectors access to all three sites.
In Vienna, it is said that the Syrians fear that the inspection group is in fact spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it was intelligence provided by U.S. secret agents that drew the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have shuttled between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could “be used for fuel production.”
It would have "no indications of sensitive activities", such as enrichment and reprocessing of uranium; processes that are indispensable to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible hypotheses regarding the following fundamental questions: where should uranium have come from and where would have been separated later the plutonium needed to make the bomb.
It is not known whether the rubble, which could hide valuable traces, was stored at all three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with dirt have disappeared, no one will have information on where the rubble will be stored.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located just a few kilometres from el-Kibar on the other side of the Euphrates River, examined in 1998 to see if it could be suitable for the storage of radioactive waste.
Recently analyzing satellite photos taken on behalf of Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley linked them to the reactor in question.
Satellite photos, however, show that Syria undertook groundwork at the three suspicious sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to those sites.
It may have been a coincidence, but it did not help to dispel suspicion.
It is said in the diplomatic circles that the IAEA has spent several months developing a plan for the inspections to be carried out, which would allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. Only the time invested shows the great interest of the inspectors in this matter.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also ignored this proposal.
A year ago, if Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported on the destruction of the reactor, the urgency would not be reported for this case, says, for example, Glyn Davies, the US ambassador who has been talking for a few months about what is known as special inspections, one of the most powerful means that the Atomic Agency has to implement.
The IAEA director, Yukiya Amano, who had to propose these inspections, has already spoken of "an option to which I am open in the future", but he is still hesitant.
This means a huge risk: on the one hand, it requires a majority in the IAEA Board of Governors and many of the 35 countries represented there do not want to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, as this diplomat who gives to reflect: "Would it be useful, if in the end they find nothing"
