Many Hatians, including many who were displaced following the January earthquake, were wandering around the neighborhood to find where to vote.
Some of them eventually gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several alleged favorites, denounced the fraud and called for the election to be cancelled.
Protests, sometimes violent, exploded across the country.
Nonetheless, Edmond Mulet, the senior official in Haiti of the United Nations, considers the event "a fairly good election in many respects."
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community have cautiously stated that they “do not believe that these irregularities, however serious, have necessarily invalidated the process.”
In other words, the show continues.
