The second round is expected in January.
All hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial appeal for the vote to be declared void.
But there may be problems if Mr Célestin, who has little or no noticeable support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second toura reaches the second round.
With a raging cholera epidemic, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, there were fears that participation would be.
In this case, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so due to disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 identity cards, needed to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The stakes are important.
Donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in Haiti’s reconstruction.
And so, it is clear, the Haitians do it themselves.
The tip of the feet towards the center
In the weeks after she suddenly became a widow, Cristina Fernández, president of Argentina, enjoyed a wave of public sympathy that improved her approval rating by 20 points to more than 50 percent, her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Yet turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on Ms. Fernández’s visibly grieving choice whether or not to abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain confusing.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to draw up budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
The Fernández government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has plunged into disarray following Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some of the dissident members of the ruling Peronist movement rallied to Ms. Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (where a parliamentarian punched one of his peers in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress does not have to approve the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to fight,” the president said.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the president even more leeway to spend at will.
The economy is largely overheating: it is likely to grow by almost 9% this year.
The official inflation rate now stands at 11.1% but many private estimates and union wage demands see this figure close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction a priority, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to deal with the IMF, harassed the private sector and purged the INDEC, the statistical office, which forged official inflation statistics.
Can Ms Fernández now moderate these policies?
She called for talks between private companies and trade union leaders.
And his officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by Argentina's high global agricultural export prices.
But inflation eroded the growth boost following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Ms. Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial relations to the rest of the world.
This year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced debt restructuring for which Argentina had not settled its maturities in 2001.
Now Ms Fernandez seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve surveillance by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index; which sounds like a prelude to the remediation of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether Ms. Fernández wants to remain in politics beyond the end of her term, now that her husband is no longer with her.
If it does, it needs to gain support from the middle class, among whom Kirchnerism is widely advocated.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have ebbed back.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to repudiate, without noise, many of her husband’s policies.
Half an hour for China
Taiwanese voters are oriented towards a kind of closer union with the continent.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother on the other side of the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters ran on Nov. 27, accounting for 70 percent of eligible voters, to elect mayors and city councillors in five urban districts, as part of what is considered an overall assessment by President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr. Ma himself has become a substitute for feelings about the continent, having forged innovative business ties, including a partial free trade pact, in the largest reorganization of relations with China proper since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but just.
Although his Kuomintang party (KMT) won three of the five mayoral elections, it failed to win the majority of the votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which has leaned towards Taiwan’s complete independence, won nearly 50% of all votes for the 45% KMT.
If it had been a presidential election, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since he was elected two years ago, his party's vote share has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP attracted voters, even with the KMT in municipal councils.
The event unveiled most of the main topics of the Taiwanese elections, including bullying campaign trucks and mass rally flags with girls dancing in minimal outfits.
An attempted compulsory murder mystery was also perpetrated.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan, honorary president of the KMT, conducted an election tour for a KMT candidate on the eve of the election.
A man from the crowd shot the young Mr. Lien, purely through the face, wounding him and killing a passerby.
