Instead, the candidates flipped with plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys its de facto independence and hates China’s military threat.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid parading its ties with the Beijing government.
But this time, the DPP also refrained from stoking anti-Chinese sentiment.
This is the answer to a new realization that Chinese companies are indispensable to Taiwan’s economic survival.
Ma, for his part, claimed confirmation as to whether his China policy was acceptable to the Taiwanese majority.
One can expect that the Beijing government will continue to provide trade facilities, in line with its strategy to deceive Taiwan back into the fold.
China wasted no time sending a negotiator to Taipei to organize a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
Of course, it would also like to see political integration; but let’s start from the beginning.
It is best to wait for this after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has reinvented itself anyway.
Two years ago, his former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was sent to prison on corruption charges.
President from 2000 to 2008, he was a provocateur in favor of explicit independence.
But a new generation of moderates has emerged under Ms. Tsai, and the PDP is making every effort to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai was hailed as a DPP presidential candidate, like Su Tseng-chang, who served under Mr. Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that it too can engage with Beijing.
Ms. Tsai announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided that their talks can take place without preconditions.
Ms. Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party presents a "trustworthy alternative" to Ma's hasty approach to China.
