The lion is ready to blush again, the restructuring of MGM is waiting for the final green light of the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start over.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York on Thursday officially praised the “pre-packaged” plan by creditors that would wipe out about $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and television shows.
With Thursday’s decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, no legal obstacles remain before MGM to get back afloat under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the CEOs of what will be a lightweight studio.
Staff will be reduced to about 320 out of 400 at the outset.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase enters into a $500 million credit facility to fund MGM’s new operations and productions.
It is currently being licensed by the investment bank, which itself runs up to $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The studio's restructuring process began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to place its finances as it could not afford to pay interest of $300 million per year.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and a recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to resolve MGM’s financial difficulties and satisfy the studio’s more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed at the end of 2009 to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the $2 billion more their creditors were looking for.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be done again as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan that, after months of disagreement and internal debate, was finally approved by creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially exits bankruptcy in the following weeks, the Moelis and Cooper companies receive multi-million-dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already secured $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper’s companies, which raised $375,000 a month for their business leadership services, will receive a “success bonus” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to relaunch MGM’s production, which has released only one film this year, and to put together an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released starting in 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", with Warner Bros.
The studio has to sign a separate loan between $265 million and $275 million to fund its share in these two films, which must be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18 percent of MGM’s debt, has attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where it is the main shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not resulted in an agreement.
