Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to get a lobbying job for the wife's husband, the senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his affair made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Mr. Ensign’s office said he was “very happy” with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator may still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he had no intention of maintaining any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's case with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer in an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a colleague of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole for one year.
Ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems to contradict the so-called ban on lobbying's revolving door.
“There appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and a substantial violation of revolving door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecution after a number of high-level setbacks received by its Public Integrity Section, including last year's decision to drop prosecution of former Senator Steven D.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the director general of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's senior lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call on Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the ministry was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign’s team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, “had acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
“I’m not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department except to say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign’s $96,000 payment by his parents in the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "hammering" the Interior Ministry on a disputed issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Transportation Secretary to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth-ranking Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department's lead and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue her hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
