In the end, the defense said there were more than 140,000 messages about the rape case trial and children tied to their bed in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was found guilty of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to lead to an official end where the judge would impose the death penalty, voted by the jury.
But Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in court that outlines appeal arguments that could occupy the courts for years.
