They maintained that the computer media continued to stoke the flames of the emotion of the case.
"The daily rush of media tweets, cameras and journalists in front of the courthouse," the lawyers wrote, "did not resemble anything that had been seen before here in New Haven, and perhaps even nationally."
Their focus on Twitter system coverage is controversial.
In the interviews, some journalists said that the claim that snapshots were more incendiary than slower releases was a Luddite view that would impoverish the Court's policy governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers said appeals courts were often drawn to arguments that social and technological changes required adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayes' lawyers insist on this claim.
In their file, they make reference to the 1966 Supreme Court decision that overturned Dr. Sheppard’s conviction because of the media coverage of the trial and they specified that they would invoke the need for new rules for new media.
“This affair,” they wrote, “represents that of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century.”
Can civility bring divisions closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a foretaste of genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the swift return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that need to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences of the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the committee on the president’s deficit was just as civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual trial and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That's why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, spending, health care or rights, both sides stay miles apart.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda for the “lame duck” session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting in the White House, more optimism hangs over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the “lame duck”, with the ratification of the “New START” pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "blade duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that have to be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what’s going on between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, according to themselves, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group; this suggests that there is little motive or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care; followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
The one who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic point of view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Leaked U.S. documents describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocracy" and passes part of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, the U.S. embassy in Russia said in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are carrying out huge rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called the “vertical of power” – takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by WikiLeaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been purged.
It was drafted while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has been little evidence of clean-up since then.
Lukhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a leading construction company, have consistently denied corruption charges over the years; and he has won several defamation lawsuits on those charges.
In September, he told a Russian television station when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s thrown away, it’s just anything.”
Russians overwhelmingly believe their society is corrupt, according to polls.
But it is unusual to find the information stated in an embassy report; and it is unheard of to conceive that it would be to diplomats of a foreign country to do so.
The direct link established between the Moscow city government and crime has led some people to call it “dysfunctional” and claim that the government functioned more like a kleptocracy than a government, according to the embassy note.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term used in the criminal world/mafia that literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor’s office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-level structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB, the MVD and the militias are at the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt detectives are at the lowest level."
“This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas where the city does not provide certain services.”
The report says the FSB is brewing money from the biggest companies and the police are targeting the small ones.
One source, he said, “explained that Moscow business owners understood that it was better to get protection from the MVD and the FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by law.”
“This is why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is no longer so high.”
The note notes that, although the collection of money is extensive, the protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their business closed under one pretext or another.
Medvedev spoke several times about the fight against corruption but admitted little progress.
The embassy note sends reports of men carrying suitcases, probably filled with money, to the Kremlin.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev is dependent on bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of Moscow's think tank Indem, in a recent interview.
"But it's part of this bureaucracy."
"He's not part of a political class because he doesn't exist in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to Indem, the cost of corruption in Russia as a whole is more than $300 billion a year.
The country was ranked 154th in a recent survey on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are ranked from the least to the most corrupt).
Disclosure of the note from the US embassy, which was only carried out yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, will certainly stir up discontent within the Russian government; although Luzhkov may be blamed, to some extent, for the Moscow failures, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed by CNN by Larry King, Putin hypothesized that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fabrication and reacted with anger to the remarks that U.S. diplomats had leaked by calling him Batman and bringing Medvedev closer to Robin.
"The problem is that this is about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he said.
“But to be honest with you, we didn’t suspect that it would be achieved with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, as opposed to ethics.”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with poor quality decrepit concrete walls, the principal of Anlong Veng High School referred to the man who built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
“He was a good leader; and he cared about his people,” said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led by the United Nations, handed down its first sentence against a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as “Duch,” to 35 years in prison.
In the face of these developments, anxiety has increased among Khmer Rouge veterans in Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their desire to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"The situation creates divisions within families."
Under the rule of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-United government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary were leading the guerrillas from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 pending trial.
Without their benefactors, most Khmer Rouge veterans have sunk into the black misery common to rural Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officers retained their positions as local leaders in exchange for laying down arms, they are unskilled farmers at low grade and record.
“These people received very little follow-up after the capitulation,” said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They are soaked in the agrarian utopian ideology of the regime.”
“They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling down in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
"Ta Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to provide for our own needs.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge court has also caused concern here.
The court is expected to begin the trial of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, early next year.
The court's mandate is to try senior officials and the main perpetrators of the crimes, but it did not say whether it was pursuing beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation has turned to 64-year-old Im Chaem, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province under the rule of the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers were reportedly killed.
Recently, on a torrid evening, Im Chaem was returning from work to the field located near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past among the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," she said.
"If there is more prosecution, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia has to dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang, from the documentation center.
“Reconciliation in Khmer terms is reconnecting the broken pieces,” he said.
“We have to put these pieces together so we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, Composed of 75 Pages."
He distributed it in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's history textbooks, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, Anlong Veng's youth know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he came home with the book to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court,” he says.
“They are wary because they don’t know exactly how many people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the manual, and the court are starting to make an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retains a powerful attraction here.
In the heights of the Dangrek Mountains, a path, overwhelmed by weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty sheet roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside mobile phone seller, said she didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many people go there to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea’s birthday and later that day she planned to walk to Pol Pot’s last resting place where she would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in hopes of bringing luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its stockpile of military-grade uranium
The Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will abandon its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a key component of nuclear weapons; this decision is part of a surprise victory of President Obama's campaign to secure nuclear materials worldwide.
