It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with objectives very far from the high automotive competition.
Named PLM, this powerful computer instrument has been used to create assembly lines from manufacturing plants around the world, power stations, high-precision instruments.
The goal is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable defects and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial division, explains the fact that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 plant has allowed Red Bull to create and execute “in a few hours, almost in real time”, the modifications, changes and improvements detected during the races and tests.
Russwurm explains that the 1992 teams had an average of 10 technicians on their teams who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements on the vehicles each season.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all kinds of modifications on the cars.
The Siemens executive explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of Red Bull cars except the engine, which is the sole responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
The changes can move from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
