On the other, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins Chancellor Angela Merkel’s criticism of her responsibility to detach the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be mentioned that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another constraint on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, in Germany we are beginning to speculate on the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, even if now it seems like science fiction, with a very favourable current of opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third, a new conception of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, fiscal rigour, fines to the countries that transgress them, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there is no room for apologies.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought should be done (fiscal tightening plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second blow by the Central European country was when Merkel hardly extended the decision to save Greece.
From that moment it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the Union treaties to make possible the rescue of a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear a share of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, because it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, was approved and, in the following months, we should witness the reform process of the Union that will make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare themselves in default and, in that case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany tells us that we must follow a strict path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just a question of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked to do is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give us greater peace of mind.
And that we know how to seize the opportunity that we were given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel’s criticisms, the thesis that it is necessary to put order at home has been paved the way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to move it.
And among the possibilities that are envisaged, one cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone too full of unserious countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it warned us.
Sport and fraud of the law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate the ingenuity but not the willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 game against Ajax in the Champions League has caused a lot of ink on the anti-sports character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is known, a few minutes before finishing the game (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, both players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next match of the playoff against Auxerre and will be able to go without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned with two matches the team's coach, José Mourinho, and different economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten, but followed, rules of this sport.
A part of the debate that arose in the related case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which on past occasions has condemned to a fine to its players for similar acts) and to the provocative dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho's histories, which adds to his story.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour does not expressly prohibit by the regulations contradict the principles of sport, that is, whether with these actions one commits a fraud of law; because, indeed, they are actions respectful of the sports regulations, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that are referred to with the correct game is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but their action has precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty from the referee.
They were waiting and willingly accepted the penalty.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders obtain from the intentional misconduct investigated.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the opponent and one does not obtain an advantage in the same match, because obviously the result of the action supposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club could not rely on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a sanction match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladders is not so clear that this is an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which still includes the making of strategic decisions that promote the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), but otherwise they chose rather the time at which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the line between genius and law fraud is blurred, on this occasion I think we've had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way of transmitting the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
