"The winners of the semifinals compete in the finals of their category."
"Then the winners of each category come together to crown one champion, the king of kung fu."
450 million in contracts without tenders
Hydro-Québec has awarded over-the-counter contracts worth $450 million to engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts, a consortium made up of the firms BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor obtained the most important, that of the project stewardship, for a sum of $295 million without bidding.
This consortium called Énergie gerence was formed in 2004 in conjunction with Hydro-Québec's decision to entrust the private sector with the responsibility of managing this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the Energy stewardship consortium won the lucrative contract without a public tender.
For the Parti Québécois, the use of consortiums of companies poses a serious ethical problem that risks eliminating competition and causing an increase in prices.
"It's the new way to collude and knock down the competition."
"In other words, people, instead of doing it secretly, now do it openly," Péquis MP Sylvain Simard told a news conference yesterday.
Earlier in the morning, Mr. Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because he says it is difficult to see how the public interest can be served in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, replied in the afternoon, vigorously denying that there was collusion for this contract.
"I'm starting to have my journey," she said, arguing that the PQ had been "dishonest" and had "lacked rigour".
She said that "it would be the least of the things" that the PQ apologizes.
The formula of consortiums is a common practice throughout the world.
It is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their respective expertise in order to respond to a call for tenders for a complex project.
The Eastmain project has a high level of complexity given the scale of the work.
The project is underway and is scheduled to run until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without competition; there was negotiation.
Therefore, the consortia formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir revealed last week, the formula for consulting engineering consortiums is being investigated by the government.
A quick overview of the Québec business register makes it possible to count more than 200 consortiums, some of which seem permanent.
For example, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIMA+, Genivar, SNC-Lavalin and other Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads back to one and the same legal entity, Dessau.
Regarding the Energy Management consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed that "James Bay responds to particular workforce dynamics and Hydro-Québec has responded in a particular way since the 1970s".
The great boss of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the James Bay Energy Society (SEBJ), gave an explanation that raised the eyebrow about the fact that the project stewardship contract was granted over-the-counter.
"If you go to tender and there are few bidders, your prices will be higher."
"You have two choices: either you take the people who are in that market and you say: we're going to negotiate a satisfactory agreement and at a good price."
"But the idea is that it's not the price that matters, it's the competence of the people," Laporte said.
This contract awarded to the Energy stewardship consortium is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Parti québécois.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or the SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
After verification, Le Devoir counted 109 consulting engineering contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to firms or their subsidiaries, including soil laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin won 22 contracts, Genivar won 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, not counting its participation in Energie gérance.
All contracts have been negotiated.
They total $449,783,344, including the $295,131,564 Energy stewardship contract.
Sylvain Simard suggested that the four firms that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well known to the Liberal Party of Quebec."
The minister Normandeau dismissed that the PQ is also linked to these firms that "fund" it, before specifying that they were rather its leaders.
Responsible Consumption Barometer - The "green" label does not inspire confidence
Greener, but frankly skeptical.
The Quebec consumer has very little confidence in sustainable development actors, but also in fair brands and eco-friendly certifications to guide his choices.
Even worse, even if he bathes in a media universe where messages in favor of more responsible consumption are rife, he deplores a lack of credible information, a deficiency that he even describes as a brake on his commitment, says the Barometer of Responsible Consumption, whose first reading was delivered yesterday.
Although they increased the consumption of so-called socially responsible products in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those who try to sell them.
Two thirds of them say they do not believe the environmental commitment of companies as well as the green advertising of companies, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Observatoire de la consommation responsable of the Université Sherbrooke.
Another finding: half of consumers doubt the reliability of official certifications on so-called fair products, but also the credibility of products and brands that appear to be eco-responsible, says the Barometer.
In the same vein, the discourse of politicians on this issue is taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebecers.
However, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this part of consumption currently animated by almost a third of Quebec consumers.
Indeed, the emptiness and dubious nature of the information would calm the ardors of 46% of consumers.
This is the second brake identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers say they are as suspicious of the alleged performance of green products or services as they are trying to get into their hands.
On another note, consumers were almost half in 2010 to have changed their habits and especially changed the brand of one or more products to meet their conviction.
At the level of 61%, they also favored purchases from merchants in their neighborhood and favored the purchase of food products grown in their region, says the Barometer.
More green and responsible - the responsible consumption index has reached 64 out of a maximum of 100 for this year - , the Homo consumus of Quebec likes to present itself as the king of recycling that seeks to reduce its environmental footprint by worrying about the protection of animals.
But his social and ecological awareness seems to remain outside his car, says the Barometer: in 2010, only 28% of Quebecers indicated that they used public transport or advocated carpooling to defend their green interests.
Walking and cycling were also supported by 39.1% of participants in this large behavioral survey, which has just taken its first snapshot.
