The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the 3rd quarter
The unemployment rate in France in the sense of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in the metropolis (9.7% counting the overseas departments), show the provisional seasonally adjusted data (CVS) published Thursday by the INSEE.
The number of unemployed stands at 2,631 million in the metropolis.
The data for the second quarter were confirmed to 9.3% of the working population in the metropolis and 9.7% with the DOM.
Over a year, the unemployment rate rose by 0.1 points.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people on the labour market has further deteriorated, with a further increase in the unemployment rate, to 24.2% in the metropolis (+ 0.9 point over three months, +0.5 point over one year) and 25% including the DOM.
In the third quarter, 637,000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the ILO.
For their part, seniors experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in the metropolis (+0.2 point over three months as well as over one year), or 482,000 people aged 50 or over, and 6.6% with the DOM.
Only 25-49-year-olds benefited from stable unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in the metropolitan area (-0.1 point over three months, +0.1 point over one year) and 8.8% in the whole of France.
INSEE has not published a monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversy over its calculation method.
On the other hand, Eurostat, the European Union's statistical agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October after 9.9% in September.
