Clotilde Reiss case: the Elysée exaggerated the mediation of Syria
For more than ten months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher arrested in Iran for "espionage", has kept opinion in the air in France, put diplomacy on alert, and accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of U.S. diplomats.
The US documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some undersides of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée explained its strategy to the Americans, going so far as to give them advice on dealing with their own “hostage” crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials tried to convince Washington that the release of the young Frenchwoman did not have as a counterpart the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detainee in France and wanted by the US justice for trafficking materials for the benefit of the Iranian nuclear program.
Finally, they put in a raw light the way the French presidency sought to manipulate the media to credit the idea that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad had played a central role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, it was nothing.
A diplomatic telegram drawn up on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French comments on how to handle hostage cases".
The Elysée’s advisor for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d’Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, talk with the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method.
They advise Americans to do the same to repatriate their own forcibly detained nationals to Iran.
"Make noise," they say, "keep hammering" in the media the words "fundamental human rights," "innocence," "immediate liberation."
It is necessary in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
“Do it all the more as the Iranians are asking you not to do it.”
Because, after attempts to talk through discrete channels, "silence will not solve anything", the Iranians are "masters in dilatory maneuvers".
Richier added that the arrest of foreigners is “a familiar Iranian tactic: taking hostages for political blackmail.”
He announced that the release of Clotilde Reiss from prison (which will take place on August 16, the day she takes refuge at the French embassy) "will require the payment of a large sum of money to the Iranians" (230,000 euros of bail).
And he says that the Elysee anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that "will worsen".
The Iranians could “in the near future arrest another one of the approximately 1,800 French citizens living in Iran,” he said.
August 28, 2009.
Clotilde Reiss has been released from prison for 12 days, but remains stranded in Iran.
The Iranian Majid Kakavand, whose extradition is being demanded by the United States for illegally smuggling sensitive electronic equipment to Iran, is being released in Paris on the orders of a judge.
The U.S. embassy, like many observers, wonders about this disturbing coincidence.
For Washington, which is stalking Iran’s clandestine networks for acquiring material for its nuclear program, the expansion of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Did France accept a bargain?
The liberation of the Iranian against that of the French?
In a new interview with Kathleen Allegrone on September 4, François Richier assures that this is not the case.
The Elysee, he said, not only “was completely taken by surprise by the judge’s decision,” but sought to oppose it.
"There was a lively exchange between the French presidency and the guard of the seals" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government can not reverse the decision" judicial, he observes.
Richier also wants to demonstrate that Majid Kakavand remains under the "close" surveillance of the French intelligence services.
The adviser to the Elysee dials a phone number, hangs up and then informs the US diplomat that the Iranian “is currently located in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian embassy”.
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysée does not spare its efforts, through press releases and “leaks” organized in the media, to make believe that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad plays an “important” and “influenced” role of “mediator”.
The Americans observe this activity not without irony, and find that the manipulation bears fruit since several press articles pass on the official French version.
A telegram dated August 25, 2009 evokes "the media 'blitz' of French officials".
On what is based so much "gratitude" expressed to Mr. Assad, asks the embassy in Paris.
“Despite their praise-filled statements, French officials privately acknowledge that they have only a vague notion of what the Syrians have actually done.”
The document then examines the reasons that prompted the Elysée to pour into this fiction.
The intense communication effort "aims to validate Sarkozy's policy of opening up to Syria," he said.
A policy launched in 2008, which "was then perceived, by many critical voices in France and abroad, as premature and unmerited."
By "exaggerating the Syrian role", Paris seeks to "demonstrate to Syria what praise it can attract by playing a constructive role in the region".
The aim is also to "sow seeds of discord between Syria and Iran".
The U.S. embassy knows this from a good source.
On August 11, François Richier told him: “Of course, we don’t know if the Syrians have done anything.”
"But we thanked them anyway."
"It should at least cause confusion among the Iranians."
