Avenger hackers and spies on diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file made up of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those of which Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi's sinisterly caricatural profile has long been for sketch-material cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should be composed of only known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous works.
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and that reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
I'm going for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, editor at Liberation), who retains as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same information that Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since heads of state can phone or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into espionage centers.
Any investigative film viewer knows this very well, and it is only out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims as much in crisis as the "bulls".
But let’s get to the deeper nature of what happened.
In Orwell’s time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had completely proved itself since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the possibility of keeping its own secrets keep it?
It is true, Georg Simmel was already saying, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to reveal everything in him.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to post any confidential information online - it would be like posting it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired (telephone) telegraph.
Video cassettes (analogue) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backwards and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) allow only to jump from chapter to chapter, that is to say by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, you get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips that it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, then, that politics and communications techniques revert to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret embassies.
Now it is the embassies that are requesting confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France trivializes its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (so-called fast-start or early financing) made by developed countries.
And the big French docks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (or 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU took the big step to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: a report detailing the action of its member states, a press conference, a major side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and valued: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of 7.2 billion euros in 2012.
But when you look at it in detail, things get more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without detriment to ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some member states whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has considered the year 2009 as a reference: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast-start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of the year 2010 are "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to spending in previous years or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
Concretely, the total amount of support from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment in terms of "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Here again, there is no rule and everyone chooses his mode of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> lent is equivalent to 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that will be given... At most, it should only be counted as its commitments.
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the EU to use the loan so extensively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> 1 to satisfy its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-through tour!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, it manages to make believe that it is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely duped...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully that will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the question of "additionality" or the way loans are accounted for will not escape.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
