The bottom line is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Centre for Cancer Research.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear from our investigation that the reality of consumers' exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is of concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were filled with pesticides and other chemicals.
